---
import ProposalLayout from '../../../layouts/ProposalLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "WebPage",
  "name": "The Story Behind the Pitch — Barry Grottis",
  "description": "15 years of digital marketing, product creation, and relentless iteration — told in full."
};
---

<ProposalLayout
  title="The Story Behind the Pitch — Barry Grottis"
  description="15 years of digital marketing, product creation, and relentless iteration. The full story."
  schema={schema}
>
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="pt-24 md:pt-32 pb-12 md:pb-16 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center">
      <div class="inline-block bg-terracotta/10 text-terracotta-dark text-xs px-4 py-2 rounded-full font-semibold mb-6 tracking-wide uppercase">
        The Full Story
      </div>
      <h1 class="proposal-hero-title mb-6">
        I Built an Entire Product<br class="hidden sm:block"/> as My Application.<br class="hidden sm:block"/> <span class="text-sage">Here's Why.</span>
      </h1>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-text-secondary max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed mb-8">
        Most people send a PDF. I dedicated all my energy and every spare moment to building a full product proposal, market analysis, competitive landscape, and financial model — because that's what I'd do if I already had the job.
      </p>

      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-center justify-center gap-4 sm:gap-6 pt-6 border-t border-border">
        <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
          <div class="w-16 h-16 rounded-full border-3 border-sage overflow-hidden shadow-sm mb-2" style="border-width:3px;">
            <img src="/images/team/barry-profile.png" alt="Barry Grottis" class="w-full h-full object-cover" decoding="async" />
          </div>
          <span class="font-bold text-text-primary text-sm">Barry Grottis</span>
          <span class="text-xs text-text-secondary">The Orchestrator</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
          <div class="w-16 h-16 rounded-full border-3 border-terracotta overflow-hidden shadow-sm bg-terracotta/10 flex items-center justify-center mb-2" style="border-width:3px;">
            <img src="/images/team/al-roberts-avatar.svg" alt="AL. Roborts" class="w-11 h-11 object-contain" decoding="async" />
          </div>
          <span class="font-bold text-text-primary text-sm">AL. Roborts</span>
          <span class="text-xs text-text-secondary">The Heavy Lifter</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CONTACT INFO BAR -->
  <section class="pb-6 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-center justify-center gap-3 sm:gap-6 py-4 px-6 bg-cream-dark/50 rounded-xl border border-border/50 text-sm text-text-secondary">
        <a href="mailto:barrydgrottis@gmail.com" class="hover:text-sage transition-colors flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M3 8l7.89 5.26a2 2 0 002.22 0L21 8M5 19h14a2 2 0 002-2V7a2 2 0 00-2-2H5a2 2 0 00-2 2v10a2 2 0 002 2z"/></svg>
          barrydgrottis@gmail.com
        </a>
        <a href="tel:02904307704" class="hover:text-sage transition-colors flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M3 5a2 2 0 012-2h3.28a1 1 0 01.948.684l1.498 4.493a1 1 0 01-.502 1.21l-2.257 1.13a11.042 11.042 0 005.516 5.516l1.13-2.257a1 1 0 011.21-.502l4.493 1.498a1 1 0 01.684.949V19a2 2 0 01-2 2h-1C9.716 21 3 14.284 3 6V5z"/></svg>
          02904307704
        </a>
        <span class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M17.657 16.657L13.414 20.9a1.998 1.998 0 01-2.827 0l-4.244-4.243a8 8 0 1111.314 0z"/><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M15 11a3 3 0 11-6 0 3 3 0 016 0z"/></svg>
          47 Mehrtens Crescent, Woodend 7691 Christchurch
        </span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PROLOGUE: BORN READY -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Prologue</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">Born Ready — Zimbabwe</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          I was born in Zimbabwe, Africa, in 1984. My father worked in the mines, so we moved constantly — all over Zimbabwe and Botswana. New towns, new schools, new people. Before I was ten, I'd already learned the most useful skill of my life: <strong>how to adapt fast.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          Sport was the constant. I played rugby, track and field, cricket — anything competitive. I was naturally athletic, but more importantly, I was <em>always training</em>. That instinct — to stay prepared, to be ready for whatever game shows up — became the rhythm of my entire life. Alongside sport, food was always at the centre of everything. Family meals, shared plates, the joy of eating together — that's where I felt most alive.
        </p>
        <p>
          In 2003, I moved to New Zealand with my parents and my brother. A fresh start in a new country, and that same instinct to adapt kicked in immediately. I didn't know it yet, but everything I'd learned growing up had been preparing me for what came next.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 1: THE SPARK -->
  <section class="spoke-section-alt">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 1</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The Spark — 2011</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          It started with a simple promise: <em>"Send an email. Make money."</em>
        </p>
        <p>
          I'd just finished studying health, fitness, and nutrition — genuinely passionate about the science of how the human body works. Then I stumbled across an information product about email marketing, and something clicked. Not about the product itself, but about the <em>mechanism</em>. The idea that you could build a system, put it in front of the right people through the right traffic channels, and revenue could follow — that hooked me instantly.
        </p>
        <p>
          The method was straightforward: build an affiliate landing page that captured emails, then send those leads to a ClickBank offer. My first product was in the health and fitness niche — a natural fit given my background. The product was called <strong>The Truth About Abs</strong> by Mike Geary, and at the time, it had been the <strong>number one selling information product on ClickBank for four to five consecutive years</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          I learned website design. I learned how to build opt-in pages with lead capture forms. I studied the mechanics of a funnel before I even knew that's what it was called. And then I waited.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 2: THE FIRST DOLLAR -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 2</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The First Dollar</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          It took a full year.
        </p>
        <p>
          Twelve months of building, tweaking, optimizing, and wondering if any of this was real. Then one day — a sale. My first commission as an affiliate marketer on ClickBank. It was $24 USD. It might as well have been the lottery. I was so ecstatic. That single notification proved something I'd suspected but couldn't confirm: <strong>this system works.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          I was hooked.
        </p>
        <p>
          The next decade became a relentless pursuit of that feeling — trying to replicate it, scale it, and turn it into something sustainable. Some campaigns worked. Most didn't. But every single one taught me something that a textbook never could.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 3: THE SEO RABBIT HOLE -->
  <section class="spoke-section-alt">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 3</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The SEO Rabbit Hole</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          I started with Microsoft Ads — they were more lenient with affiliate marketers than Google, which made them the natural entry point. But with a small budget, there's really only one option: <strong>organic growth.</strong> A small budget isn't enough for thorough paid testing. So I dove headfirst into SEO.
        </p>
        <p>
          Timing was not on my side. I entered the SEO world right after Google's <strong>Panda and Penguin updates</strong> — the updates that wiped out the affiliate gold rush. Before those updates, people were ranking affiliate pages for health and fitness products on Google with almost reckless abandon. By the time I arrived, the mine was closed.
        </p>
        <p>
          So I adapted. I learned to build websites optimized for search, studied how rankings actually worked post-Penguin, and started playing the long game. I stayed in the health and fitness niche, testing different products and different angles — but the core strategy was always SEO. Finding the organic channels others ignored, thinking creatively about distribution instead of just buying traffic. That experience — that mindset — is the same one Cupla is looking for. <strong>Not "more content." Better angles. Smarter channels.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 4: PRODUCT #1 -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-terracotta-dark bg-terracotta/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 4</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">Product #1 — The Hard Lesson</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          I saw how well The Truth About Abs sold and thought: I can do that. I'd studied nutrition. I understood the science. So I spent the better part of a year writing a comprehensive exercise and nutrition eBook. Put it out there. Waited.
        </p>
        <p>
          Nothing.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Truth About Abs didn't just have a good product — it had a <strong>great hook</strong>. People wanted to know the truth about abs. Sharp copy. Strong marketing. My eBook had none of that. I thought quality was enough. It isn't. Without a clear hook, without a compelling reason for someone to care — even the best product gathers dust.
        </p>
        <p>
          That lesson changed everything. I was tired of promoting other people's products. I wanted to create my own — with a unique angle, a unique perspective, something I could actually believe in. The first time I started thinking about finding gaps nobody else had filled.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 5: PRODUCT #2 -->
  <section class="spoke-section-alt">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-terracotta-dark bg-terracotta/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 5</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">Product #2 — The Achilles Heel</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          In 2014, while completing my second course in health, fitness, and nutrition, I suffered an <strong>Achilles rupture</strong> — right in the middle of a rugby game. The same sport that had defined my life as a young adult — in Zimbabwe and in New Zealand — had just put me on the sidelines.
        </p>
        <p>
          During rehabilitation, I noticed a gap: <strong>tendinitis</strong>. Stage one of a rupture. People were searching for solutions to a problem that hadn't been properly addressed. I spent another year creating a comprehensive eBook and launched it on ClickBank.
        </p>
        <p>
          Same result. The market didn't care about belief — it cared about demand, positioning, and timing.
        </p>
        <p>
          Between 2014 and 2019, I dove deeper into <strong>marketing and copywriting</strong> — devouring books on direct response, studying sales letters, honing my craft. I ran affiliate marketing through SEO, but I was always looking for a product I could create myself. Something unique. Something I could believe in.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 6: THE OFFLINE EXPERIMENT -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 6</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The Offline Experiment</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          I tried something completely different: a newspaper ad targeting older demographics interested in alternative health remedies. The ad directed them to call a hotline and leave their details. I'd then ship them a printed pamphlet — a long-form sales pitch for a physical supplement I was drop-shipping.
        </p>
        <p>
          I made exactly <strong>two sales</strong>. One from a reader. The other from the person at the printing press who read the pamphlet and bought on the spot.
        </p>
        <p>
          But I also discovered what I was doing wrong. The funnel was too long. People answered a printed ad, called a number, got a pamphlet — and then I was asking them to go <em>online</em> to order the supplement. Print to phone to paper to web. Too many steps. Too much friction.
        </p>
        <p>
          Customer acquisition cost far exceeded revenue. The lesson: <strong>good copy sells, but the channel is the vehicle.</strong> Offline was expensive and slow. Online offered quick, cheap channels — even free ones like SEO. That lesson stuck with me.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 7: PRODUCT #3 -->
  <section class="spoke-section-alt">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-terracotta-dark bg-terracotta/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 7</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">Product #3 — The Carb Insight</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          By this point, I was done with affiliate marketing. Tired of pushing other people's products that often felt scammy. I wanted to create something I could stand behind.
        </p>
        <p>
          I wrote <strong>The 28-Day Carb Challenge</strong>. The idea came from watching two extremes collide: keto was exploding (carbs are the enemy), while a growing movement was promoting high-carb diets (pasta, bread, even sugar were back). I have a sweet tooth. I love carbs. The idea appealed to me.
        </p>
        <p>
          But I didn't want extremes. Your body needs carbs, fat, and protein — all of it. The science backed this up. The <strong>Rice Diet</strong> by Walter Kempner — originally for hypertension, but it produced tremendous weight loss. Modern interpretations by Nathan Pritikin and Dr. John McDougall. Nobody had branded it as a challenge. I saw the gap and moved.
        </p>
        <p>
          The hook: <em>tired of keto? Eat carbs and still lose weight.</em> Behind the hook, the bigger idea: it's about proportion, not elimination.
        </p>
        <p>
          But the real breakthrough wasn't the diet. It was the <strong>sales mechanism</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          I offered a free eBook as an opt-in. After signing up, visitors were redirected to a <strong>one-time offer</strong> — the <strong>exact same page</strong>. Word for word. Same copy, same images. The only difference: instead of a free product for an email, it was asking them to pay for the full version. They'd already raised their hand. They wanted it.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>People signed up for the free eBook, saw the paid offer on the very next page, and bought it — before they'd even read the free one.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          When people are hot — when they've just said "yes, I want this" — offer them a bigger version of the same thing and they'll take it. Heat equals conversion. <strong>Strike when the iron is hot, and make the next step obvious.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 8: THE AI PIVOT -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 8</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The AI Pivot</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          In the early 2020s, I was introduced to ChatGPT. I immediately started thinking about how to use it to create content — just like everyone else at the time. But I also saw something deeper: <strong>a new market was forming.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          I devoured content on AI. I followed the creators pushing the boundaries. My initial idea was practical — use AI to help build websites, particularly the WordPress sites I'd been running since 2011.
        </p>
        <p>
          As I explored, I went deeper. I learned how AI models actually work — context windows, capabilities, mixture-of-experts architecture, how they were trained. I discovered harnesses like Roo Code, Kilo Code, and Open Code that let you code inside an IDE, access files, and autonomously execute tasks. The more I learned, the more I saw the potential for AI to fundamentally change how digital products are created and marketed.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 9: THE ACCELERATION -->
  <section class="spoke-section-alt">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 9</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The Acceleration — 2026</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          At the start of 2026, everything accelerated.
        </p>
        <p>
          I was using AI assistants like Roo Code, Kilo Code, and Open Code inside VS Code — integrating them directly into my workflow. WordPress had been my foundation for over a decade, but the landscape was shifting and I was moving along with it. The entire AI ecosystem was exploding — models, harnesses, image generation, video generation — and I was riding the wave.
        </p>
        <p>
          Then in March, I made a move that surprised even me. <strong>I pivoted away from the technologies I'd been accustomed to for over a decade.</strong> Other systems and integrations worked better with AI, and I wasn't going to let loyalty to old tools hold me back.
        </p>
        <p>
          Within weeks, I'd developed a system for building fully SEO-optimized websites with custom designs and AI-generated images — completed in <strong>a couple of hours</strong>. Sometimes less.
        </p>
        <p>
          That led to a new business: building websites, setting up automation, email marketing, and digital infrastructure for local service-based businesses. I started approaching potential clients, looking for opportunities.
        </p>
        <p>
          I wasn't just technically interested in AI — I was interested in what it could <em>do</em>. As I learned alongside it, I saw the market shifting and knew I needed to shift with it. And I did. It aligned perfectly with everything I'd been learning and trying to do for the past fifteen years.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 10: THE RECURRING DREAM -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 10</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The Recurring Dream</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          I have this dream. It comes back, again and again.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm back on the rugby field. Big tournament. Crowd's roaring. I'm supposed to be ready — I always was. I played provincial rugby in Zimbabwe, and then again in New Zealand. I was <em>always</em> training. Always prepared for the next game.
        </p>
        <p>
          But in the dream, I haven't trained in years. The game is happening <em>right now</em>, and I can feel it — my body isn't ready. My mind isn't ready. I'm standing on the field knowing I should have been preparing, and I wasn't.
        </p>
        <p>
          It's a very distressing dream — frustrating because in my mind, I should have always been ready. And I find myself unprepared. And it's <em>always</em> the same.
        </p>
        <p>
          Here's what I've come to understand: <strong>it was never about rugby.</strong> It was about readiness. About staying in shape for whatever game shows up next. And for the last fifteen years — through every failed product, every SEO campaign, every sales letter I handwritten to study copywriting, every book on direct response I devoured, every late night learning AI systems — <strong>I've been training.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          I just didn't know what game I was training for. Until now.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 11: THE MOMENT -->
  <section class="spoke-section-alt">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-terracotta-dark bg-terracotta/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 11</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The Moment</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          I was scrolling through SEEK, looking for potential businesses to approach for my services, when I saw it.
        </p>
        <p>
          A job listing from Cupla. <strong>Growth Marketer.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          I've never liked looking at job listings. They've always felt depressing — rigid, corporate, soulless. Every job I've ever seen felt like a box I didn't fit into. My skills — SEO, direct response, product development, AI automation — didn't match what most employers were looking for. I'd never felt like I had a place in the traditional job market.
        </p>
        <p>
          But this one was different. It read like it was written <em>for</em> me. Organic growth thinking. Creative distribution. SEO as a creative discipline, not a checkbox. Hands-on doer. Technically curious past the default output. Finding the angle nobody else sees.
        </p>
        <p>
          It stopped me cold. Unlike any job before — normally, a job feels like an unpassionate thing. This one sung out to me. Everything I'd been learning and doing for 15 years — the marketing, the product development, the SEO, the direct response copywriting, the AI automation, the dozens of copywriting books, the handwritten sales letters, the experiments in organic and paid channels — it all converged on that single job description.
        </p>
        <p>
          I've always wanted to be a successful entrepreneur. That's why I've never been keen on a job — I've always wanted to build my own business. But reading Cupla's description, I realized the skills I've built translate directly. I would welcome the opportunity to not just work for Cupla, but to <strong>be part of it</strong> — to be mentored by entrepreneurs who have already succeeded. To feel like I'm part of something, using the skills I have, contributing to a mission I believe in.
        </p>
        <p>
          I went into instant marketing mode.
        </p>
        <p>
          Not "update my resume" mode. Not "write a cover letter" mode. <em>Marketing</em> mode. The same instinct that kicked in when I saw The Truth About Abs, when I identified the carb diet gap, when I realized AI could automate website builds — that same instinct said: <strong>find the unique angle. Build something nobody else would build. Make it impossible to ignore.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          So I did what any growth marketer worth their salt would do. I didn't apply. <strong>I demonstrated.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 12: FAMILY & MOTIVATION -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 12</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">Family & Motivation</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          Everything I do comes back to one thing: <strong>looking after my family.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          I have three children. A teenage boy who's figuring out who he is. A seven-year-old with special needs who requires more patience and care than most people will ever understand. And a toddler who's just starting primary school — wide-eyed, full of energy, still figuring out the world. They're the reason I get up at all.
        </p>
        <p>
          My parents are retired. They came to New Zealand late in life after building up lives in another country, and they arrived here basically with nothing. They sacrificed everything for a fresh start. Watching that — watching them rebuild from zero — shaped my entire work ethic. I don't take opportunities for granted because I know what it costs to create them.
        </p>
        <p>
          If I was given the opportunity to work for Cupla, all I would ask for is fair compensation. That's it. Not extravagance. Not status. Just fair compensation for my knowledge and my work, so I can provide for the people who depend on me.
        </p>
        <p>
          I've never wanted to be a worker. A number. A statistic. A figure on a spreadsheet. Most jobs I've encountered felt exactly like that — and I couldn't do it. Not because I'm above it, but because I know I have more to give than a slot on an org chart.
        </p>
        <p>
